body:
We are using the Az modules heavily. So we really would like to see the strictness applied to the Az modules as well.

@powercode It seems PowerShell is lacking named parameters with class methods. So readability is impacted if we move away from regular functions.

@SeeminglyScience I guess c# would be an option if we were able to just ship the c# as a script.  There was already csx, and now with c# there is this top-level program feature.

We are also considering moving to nodejs which gives a perfect solution for all of this. Unfortunately the Az modules nodejs equivalent last time we checked (August 2020) were not very mature and incomplete (https://azure.github.io/azure-sdk-for-js/). Nodejs brings us:
1. Compatibility with Azure Pipelines; it is providing a nodejs task runner;
2. Perfect module import semantics;
3. Strict function signature checking.
I guess we need to revisit this area. It looks like the past few months they didn't stand still!

If we would be able to mix our PowerShell with dotnet code, I guess that we then would hit the dotnet Azure sdk also lagging behind the az cli and az PowerShell modules surfaces.

<blockquote><img src="https://c.s-microsoft.com/favicon.ico?v2" width="48" align="right"><div><strong><a href="https://azure.github.io/azure-sdk-for-js/">Azure SDK for JavaScript | Azure SDK for JavaScript</a></strong></div></blockquote>

@SeeminglyScience albeit unrelated to my OP, if the runspace is shared, then there are two things not clear to me:
1. Why is the completion support on the cmdlets so different in the editor and on the prompt? On the prompt is so much better, so much faster.
2. Where is the pesky delay coming from when I press F8 from the editor? Sometimes it takes many seconds before the selected text get passed to the prompt.
